  <text>
    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Sunday 1/2 pst 5 o'clock</p>
      <p>Dearest William. My cold became so much worse last night, &amp; still more so this morning, accompanied with much heat, that I have been obliged to stop it vigorously.</p>
      <p>The measures I took have answered well, but have brought on much local uneasiness which makes it necessary for me to keep</p>
      <p>quite flat this evening, otherwise mischief might follow. This will account for my pencil note, but you must not be the least uneasy, for I have only now to keep quiet, and I do not think that I shall lay my egg for some days yet! Hester is a great comfort to me, &amp; indeed I do not know what I should do without her, both our young &amp; our servants being so inaccessible to me here.--</p>
      <p>I am in hopes you will have very pleasant weather. In Town today it is rather too mild.--</p>
      <p>The Hen continues to require</p>
      <p>more bleeding, but the relief it gives her is very great, &amp; it seems quite necessary.-- She has had an amusing letter from Miss Murray, who is delighted with the unchanged simplicity of the Queen's manners, &amp; her perfect official dignity withal. She says "it seems to be the Queen's first object to make everybody about her happy". She is certainly a marvellous character for eighteen.--</p>
      <p>I miss you sadly. I think it gets worse every absence. The poor bird to sing when her master is away.-- I am afraid this is not a very</p>
      <p>entertaining letter, but the incidents up here in Mont Blanc are few &amp; not remarkable.-- The avis will of course write tomorrow.--</p>
      <p>Bird</p>
    </div></body>
